docs.lead_paragraph: New Jersey has surpassed its goal of enrolling an additional 50,000 children in the state’s health insurance program by July, state officials said yesterday. Jennifer Velez, the acting human services commissioner, said 96,000 additional children had enrolled in the program since Gov. Jon S. Corzine announced the goal in February 2006. The program, NJ FamilyCare, provides free or low-cost health insurance to people, depending on their income. Currently, 536,102 children and 163,303 adults are covered.
